+# D.U.H. Architecture
+
+D.U.H. (Duh is a Universal Harness) is a provider-agnostic AI coding
+agent. This document describes the structure of the codebase at commit
+`645d91a`: what lives where, how a single user request flows from the
+CLI down to a model response and back, where to plug in new behaviour,
+how the security model is organised, and which tradeoffs the project
+has made.
+
+It is intended to be read top-to-bottom. Later sections assume the
+vocabulary of the earlier ones.
+
+---
+
+## 1. The top-level layout
+
+The package layout under `duh/`:
+
+```
+duh/
+├── kernel/        Provider-agnostic agentic core. Stdlib-only.
+├── ports/         Abstract interfaces the kernel depends on.
+├── adapters/      Concrete implementations of ports.
+├── providers/     Registry + runtime provider selection.
+├── tools/         Built-in tool implementations.
+├── cli/           argparse entrypoint, REPL, slash commands, batch mode.
+├── ui/            Textual-based TUI (app, modals, themes).
+├── bridge/        SDK/NDJSON bridge server + session relay.
+├── security/      Policy engine, trifecta, sandboxes, scanners.
+├── auth/          OAuth & API-key storage for Anthropic + OpenAI.
+├── plugins/       Plugin registry.
+├── hooks.py       Lifecycle event bus (HookEvent / HookRegistry).
+├── agents.py      Sub-agent spawning helpers.
+├── constitution.py Global safety text (injected into system prompt).
+├── config.py      Config discovery + merging.
+└── cli/main.py    `duh` console_scripts entry point.
+```
+
+### Component diagram
+
+```
+┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
+│                         duh.cli.main                            │
+│              (argparse → runner | repl | batch)                 │
+└──────────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────┘
+                               │
+        ┌──────────────────────┼─────────────────────────┐
+        ▼                      ▼                         ▼
+  duh.cli.runner         duh.cli.repl              duh.cli.batch
+  (print mode)     (interactive, Rich/TUI)    (stream-json / NDJSON)
+        │                      │                         │
+        └──────────────────────┴─────────────────────────┘
+                               │
+                               ▼
+                  ┌────────────────────────────┐
+                  │    duh.cli.session_builder │
+                  │  (wires Deps + EngineConfig)│
+                  └──────────────┬─────────────┘
+                                 │
+        ┌────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────┐
+        │                        │                         │
+        ▼                        ▼                         ▼
+ duh.ports.ModelProvider  duh.ports.ToolExecutor    duh.ports.ApprovalGate
+ (injected as             (injected as              (injected as
+   deps.call_model)          deps.run_tool)             deps.approve)
+        │                        │                         │
+ duh.adapters.anthropic   duh.adapters.native_executor   duh.adapters.approvers
+ .openai, .gemini,        .mcp_executor                  .{Auto,Rule,Tiered,Interactive}
+ .groq, .ollama,                 │
+ .stub_provider                  ▼
+                          duh.tools.{read, write, edit,
+                                     bash, grep, glob, …}
+                                 │
+                                 ▼
+                          duh.kernel.Tool  ─ protocol
+                          duh.kernel.tool.ToolResult
+
+                  ┌────────────────────────────┐
+                  │     duh.kernel.Engine      │◀─ EngineConfig, Deps
+                  │  session, turns, history   │
+                  │  budget, cost, compact     │
+                  └──────────────┬─────────────┘
+                                 │
+                                 ▼
+                  ┌────────────────────────────┐
+                  │     duh.kernel.query()     │
+                  │  the universal loop        │
+                  │  (provider-agnostic)       │
+                  └──────────────┬─────────────┘
+                                 ▼
+                        stream of events
+                        → Renderer.handle()
+                          (PlainRenderer / RichRenderer / TUI)
+```
+
+Three things make this diagram readable:
+
+1. **The kernel depends only on ports.** Dotted lines from the kernel
+   to adapters do not exist. If you grep `duh/kernel/*.py` for
+   `from duh.adapters`, every hit is inside `if TYPE_CHECKING:` or
+   inside a function body for lazy optional imports (e.g.
+   `Engine._get_adaptive_compactor`).
+2. **Everything crosses the kernel boundary through `Deps`.** The
+   `Deps` dataclass (`duh.kernel.deps.Deps`) has one field per port.
+   Session startup wires them; the kernel uses them.
+3. **The CLI owns composition.** `duh.cli.session_builder` knows
+   which provider the user picked, which approver to use, which tool
+   registry is active. The kernel never makes those choices.
+
+---
+
+## 2. Data flow of a single user request
+
+Trace one user turn from a REPL prompt to rendered output.
+
+### 2.1 Parsing and dispatch
+
+```
+user types prompt
+        │
+        ▼
+ duh.cli.parser.build_parser  ← one-shot argparse
+        │
+        ▼
+ duh.cli.main.main  ← dispatches on --print, --stream-json, repl default
+```
+
+For the REPL, `duh.cli.repl.run_repl` loops: it reads a line from
+`input()`, recognises slash commands via
+`duh.cli.slash_commands.SlashDispatcher.dispatch`, and otherwise
+feeds the text into `engine.run(prompt)`.
+
+Each prompt is wrapped in an `UntrustedStr` with source
+`TaintSource.USER_INPUT` by `_wrap_user_input` before it enters the
+engine; this is the only entry point that produces untainted input.
+
+### 2.2 Session setup (first turn only)
+
+`SessionBuilder` does the following in order, all inside the REPL
+process:
+
+1. Resolve the provider (Anthropic, OpenAI, Gemini, Groq, Ollama,
+   LiteLLM, or the in-tree `StubProvider`) via
+   `duh.providers.registry`.
+2. Build a `ModelProvider` adapter; its `stream()` coroutine becomes
+   `deps.call_model`.
+3. Build a `NativeExecutor` seeded with the built-in tool list from
+   `duh.tools.ALL_TOOLS` (and any MCP tools discovered from
+   `.duh/mcp.json`). Its `run()` method becomes `deps.run_tool`.
+4. Pick an `ApprovalGate` — `AutoApprover`, `TieredApprover`,
+   `RuleApprover`, or `InteractiveApprover` — based on the
+   `--approval-mode` flag. Its `check()` method becomes
+   `deps.approve`.
+5. Optionally wire an `AdaptiveCompactor` (lazy, built on demand)
+   as `deps.compact`.
+6. Attach a `HookRegistry`, optional `AuditLogger`,
+   `ConfirmationMinter`, and `StructuredLogger`.
+7. Call `check_trifecta(caps, acknowledged=...)` inside
+   `Engine.__init__` — the session refuses to start when
+   `READ_PRIVATE | READ_UNTRUSTED | NETWORK_EGRESS` are all present
+   without explicit acknowledgement.
+
+### 2.3 `Engine.run()` — per turn
+
+For each user message, `Engine.run` performs this sequence:
+
+1. **`_begin_turn`** appends the `UserMessage`, bumps the turn counter,
+   and updates the incremental token cache
+   (`_msg_token_cache` keyed by `Message.id`).
+2. Yield a synthetic `{"type": "session", ...}` event, then fire the
+   `SETUP` (once) and `TASK_CREATED` hooks.
+3. **Auto-compact** when `input_estimate > 80 % * context_window`. If
+   `deps.compact` is `None`, lazily build an `AdaptiveCompactor`.
+4. **Context gate** — build a `ContextGate(context_limit)` and
+   `check(token_estimate)`. If the ratio ≥ `0.95`, yield
+   `{"type": "context_blocked", "message": …}` and stop.
+5. Enter `_run_with_ptl_retry`, which calls `query(...)` inside a
+   PTL retry loop (prompt-too-long). On a PTL error it progressively
+   compacts to 70 %, 50 %, 30 % of the context window over up to
+   `MAX_PTL_RETRIES = 3` attempts.
+6. On overload / rate-limit, if a `fallback_model` was configured,
+   `_run_fallback` retries once against the fallback. Hooks and
+   auto-memory are disabled on the fallback path.
+7. On successful completion, fire `TASK_COMPLETED`, record
+   per-turn tokens in `_turn_token_history`, emit any budget events
+   (`budget_warning` at 80 %, `budget_exceeded` at 100 %),
+   auto-save the session via `SessionStore.save`, and, if
+   `auto_memory=True`, call `extract_memories` and yield an
+   `auto_memory` event.
+
+### 2.4 The inner loop — `duh.kernel.loop.query`
+
+`query()` is a 180-line async generator. For each turn it:
+
+1. Calls `deps.call_model(messages=..., system_prompt=..., model=...,
+   tools=..., thinking=..., tool_choice=...)` and streams events.
+2. Re-yields `text_delta`, `thinking_delta`, and the low-level
+   `content_block_*` events unchanged.
+3. When it sees an `assistant` event it captures the `Message`,
+   extracts tool-use blocks via `_extract_tool_use_blocks`, and
+   returns immediately on `_is_partial(assistant_message)`.
+4. If there are no tool-use blocks, yields
+   `{"type": "done", "stop_reason": …}` and returns.
+5. Otherwise it runs the tools. **Read-only tools** (whose
+   `is_read_only = True`) are grouped and dispatched concurrently via
+   `asyncio.gather(_execute_block(...))`. **Mutating tools** run
+   sequentially through `_execute_block_stream`, which yields the
+   `tool_use` and `tool_result` events itself.
+6. Both paths call `deps.approve` first; on denial they yield a
+   `tool_result` with `is_error=True` and `"Tool use denied: …"` as
+   content. The `PERMISSION_REQUEST` and `PERMISSION_DENIED` hooks
+   fire here.
+7. Both paths also call `deps.confirm_gate` (`resolve_confirmation`
+   in `duh.security.policy`) before execution; a gate returning
+   `action="block"` produces the same kind of error result.
+8. Results are truncated to `MAX_RESULT_SIZE = 80_000` chars before
+   being packed into a synthetic user message
+   (`{"type": "tool_result_message"}`) which the engine captures but
+   does **not** re-yield to the consumer.
+9. Loop until `max_turns` (default `1000`). If reached, a grace turn
+   runs with `tools=[]` so the model can produce a final text
+   summary before `{"type": "done", "stop_reason": "max_turns"}`.
+
+### 2.5 Rendering
+
+The events flow out through `Engine.run` back into the CLI loop.
+The renderer is one of:
+
+- `PlainRenderer` (`duh.cli.repl_renderers.PlainRenderer`) — bare
+  stdout with minimal ANSI.
+- `RichRenderer` (`duh.cli.repl_renderers.RichRenderer`) — uses the
+  `rich` library: panels, spinners, markdown rendering.
+- `duh.ui.app.DuhApp` — Textual TUI with modals, file tree, command
+  palette, theming.
+
+Each implements `duh.ports.renderer.Renderer.handle(event)` and
+dispatches to the specific `render_*` methods. `render_text_delta`,
+`render_tool_use`, `render_tool_result`, `render_thinking`,
+`render_error`, and `render_permission_request` are the core six.
+
+### 2.6 Post-turn housekeeping
+
+After `done`, the engine:
+
+1. Appends per-turn tokens to `_turn_token_history`.
+2. Feeds provider `usage` metadata into `CacheTracker.record_usage`.
+3. If auto-compaction just ran, `CacheTracker.notify_compaction`
+   suppresses the false-positive cache break on the next turn.
+4. `CompactStats.record` accumulates statistics per tier
+   (`snip`, `summary`, `microcompact`, `dedup`).
+5. `FileTracker.track` records every `Read`/`Write`/`Edit` from the
+   `NativeExecutor`, so a later `/changes` can run `git diff --stat`
+   across exactly that set.
+
+---
+
+## 3. Extension points
+
+Three kinds of extension are first-class: provider adapters, tools,
+and slash commands. A fourth — skills — is a zero-code markdown
+extension. A fifth — hooks — lets you run shell commands on lifecycle
+events without modifying the kernel.
+
+### 3.1 Adding a new provider adapter
+
+An adapter implements `duh.ports.provider.ModelProvider`. The simplest
+working example in-tree is `duh.adapters.stub_provider.StubProvider`
+(89 lines). The contract:
+
+```python
+from duh.ports.provider import ModelProvider
+
+class MyProvider:  # implements ModelProvider (Protocol)
+    async def stream(
+        self,
+        *,
+        messages: list[Any],
+        system_prompt: str | list[str] = "",
+        model: str = "",
+        tools: list[Any] | None = None,
+        thinking: dict | None = None,
+        max_tokens: int | None = None,
+        **kwargs,
+    ):
+        # Translate `messages` to the provider's native format,
+        # issue a streaming call, and yield events in D.U.H.'s
+        # uniform schema.
+        yield {"type": "text_delta", "text": "hello"}
+        yield {"type": "assistant", "message": Message(
+            role="assistant",
+            content=[{"type": "text", "text": "hello"}],
+            metadata={"stop_reason": "end_turn", "model": model},
+        )}
+        yield {"type": "done", "stop_reason": "end_turn", "turns": 1}
+```
+
+Required event types are `text_delta`, optionally `thinking_delta`,
+`tool_use`, `assistant`, and `done`. On error, yield
+`{"type": "error", "error": str}` and stop iterating.
+
+To register the adapter so the CLI can pick it, add a name to the
+provider-resolution table in `duh.providers.registry` and expose a
+`build_model_backend` branch. You can bypass this plumbing for
+testing by passing the adapter's `stream` method directly to `Deps`:
+
+```python
+deps = Deps(call_model=MyProvider().stream, run_tool=executor.run)
+```
+
+Reference adapters live in `duh/adapters/`:
+`anthropic.py`, `openai.py`, `openai_chatgpt.py`, `gemini.py`,
+`groq.py`, `ollama.py`, `litellm_provider.py`, and
+`stub_provider.py`. They all do the same four things: translate
+messages, call the SDK/REST, parse the streaming response, and
+handle provider-specific errors.
+
+### 3.2 Adding a new tool
+
+A tool implements `duh.kernel.tool.Tool`. Required attributes:
+`name: str`, `description: str`, `input_schema: dict[str, Any]`, and
+an `async def call(input, context: ToolContext) -> ToolResult`.
+
+The simplest built-in is `duh.tools.task_tool.TaskTool` (≈120 lines).
+Minimum viable skeleton:
+
+```python
+from duh.kernel.tool import ToolContext, ToolResult
+from duh.security.trifecta import Capability
+
+class MyTool:
+    name = "MyTool"
+    description = "One-sentence description the model will see."
+    capabilities = Capability.NONE        # or | combos
+    input_schema = {
+        "type": "object",
+        "properties": {
+            "arg": {"type": "string", "description": "…"},
+        },
+        "required": ["arg"],
+    }
+
+    @property
+    def is_read_only(self) -> bool:
+        return True     # enables concurrent dispatch in query()
+
+    async def call(self, input, context: ToolContext) -> ToolResult:
+        return ToolResult(output=f"got {input['arg']}")
+```
+
+Tools with `capabilities` fields feed into the trifecta computation.
+`READ_TOOLS` get auto-approval in `SUGGEST` mode; `WRITE_TOOLS` in
+`AUTO_EDIT`; `COMMAND_TOOLS` always require approval outside
+`FULL_AUTO`. These classifications are defined in
+`duh.kernel.tool_categories` as frozensets and referenced everywhere
+else.
+
+To make the tool available at runtime, add it to
+`duh.tools.__init__.ALL_TOOLS` or register it with a live executor:
+
+```python
+from duh.adapters.native_executor import NativeExecutor
+
+executor = NativeExecutor()
+executor.register(MyTool())
+```
+
+Schema validation runs via
+`duh.kernel.schema_validator.validate_tool_schema(name, schema)` —
+call it in tests to catch malformed schemas early. A `ValueError`
+subclass `SchemaValidationError` is raised for fatal issues; a list
+of strings is returned for suggestions.
+
+### 3.3 Adding a new slash command
+
+Slash commands live in `duh.cli.slash_commands.SlashDispatcher`.
+Each command is a method with the signature
+`_handle_<name>(self, arg: str) -> tuple[bool, str]`, where the tuple
+is `(should_continue, new_model_or_sentinel)`.
+
+A handler is registered by adding an entry to the class attribute
+`_HANDLERS: dict[str, Callable[[SlashDispatcher, str], _HandlerResult]]`
+at the bottom of the module. The canonical help text
+(`SLASH_COMMANDS`) must gain a matching entry — a regression test in
+`tests/unit/test_registry_unified.py` asserts the two stay in sync.
+
+```python
+class SlashDispatcher:
+    def _handle_hello(self, arg: str) -> tuple[bool, str]:
+        sys.stdout.write(f"  hello {arg or 'world'}\n")
+        return True, self.ctx.model
+
+SlashDispatcher._HANDLERS["/hello"] = SlashDispatcher._handle_hello
+SLASH_COMMANDS["/hello"] = "Print a hello message."
+```
+
+The TUI reuses the same table via
+`SlashDispatcher.async_dispatch(name, arg)`, which runs the sync
+handler with a stdout-capture buffer. If the handler must await
+something (e.g. `SessionStore.list_sessions()`), implement an
+async version and register it in `_ASYNC_HANDLERS`.
+
+### 3.4 Adding a skill
+
+Skills are zero-code — just a markdown file with YAML frontmatter.
+Location precedence (last wins by name):
+
+1. `~/.claude/skills/`
+2. `~/.config/duh/skills/`
+3. `<cwd>/.claude/skills/`
+4. `<cwd>/.duh/skills/`
+
+Both `skills/foo.md` and `skills/foo/SKILL.md` layouts are supported.
+`duh.kernel.skill.load_all_skills(cwd)` returns the deduplicated
+`list[SkillDef]`. A skill's `render(arguments)` replaces `$ARGUMENTS`
+in its body with the user's input.
+
+### 3.5 Hooks
+
+`duh.hooks.HookRegistry` emits `HookEvent` values on key lifecycle
+transitions (`PRE_TOOL_USE`, `POST_TOOL_USE`, `SESSION_START`,
+`SESSION_END`, `TASK_CREATED`, `PERMISSION_REQUEST`, `PRE_COMPACT`,
+`POST_COMPACT`, `AUDIT`, and a couple dozen more). Hooks can be
+shell commands or Python callables, configured via the user's
+`.duh/hooks.json`. One failing hook never blocks the others — error
+isolation is a project invariant.
+
+---
+
+## 4. Security architecture
+
+The security model has four layers.
+
+### 4.1 Taint propagation: `UntrustedStr`
+
+Every string that crosses the trust boundary is wrapped in an
+`UntrustedStr` with a `TaintSource` tag. Tainted sources are
+`MODEL_OUTPUT`, `TOOL_OUTPUT`, `FILE_CONTENT`, `MCP_OUTPUT`,
+`NETWORK`; untainted sources are `USER_INPUT` and `SYSTEM`.
+
+`UntrustedStr` overrides every str-returning method (`__add__`,
+`__mod__`, `format`, `join`, `replace`, `split`, `lower`, `upper`,
+`__getitem__`, `__format__`, etc.) so the tag survives normal
+operations. `merge_source(a, b)` is the propagation rule: tainted
+wins over untainted.
+
+The policy engine (`duh.security.policy.resolve_confirmation`)
+inspects the taint of any string argument to a dangerous tool call,
+and refuses it without a valid confirmation token (see next section).
+Runtime enforcement is toggled via `DUH_TAINT_STRICT=1`;
+`DUH_TAINT_DEBUG=1` logs preservation events to stderr.
+
+### 4.2 Confirmation tokens
+
+`duh.kernel.confirmation.ConfirmationMinter` generates HMAC-bound,
+single-use, 5-minute-TTL tokens of the shape
+`duh-confirm-<unix_ts>-<hmac16>`. The signed payload is
+`session_id | tool_name | sha256(input_json) | timestamp`.
+
+Only user-origin events mint tokens. `validate()`:
+
+- Rejects if the token has already been consumed (`self._issued`).
+- Rejects if `time.time() - ts > 300`.
+- Rejects if the HMAC doesn't verify against the exact
+  session-id, tool-name, or sorted JSON input it was issued for.
+- Marks the token as issued on the first successful check.
+
+Engine-level wiring is in `Engine._check_confirmation_gate`, which
+delegates to `duh.security.policy.resolve_confirmation` and receives
+a `PolicyDecision` back; `action="block"` translates into a
+tool-level denial.
+
+### 4.3 Sandbox layers
+
+Tools can opt into OS-level isolation through
+`duh.adapters.sandbox`:
+
+- `duh.adapters.sandbox.seatbelt` — macOS `sandbox-exec` profiles.
+- `duh.adapters.sandbox.landlock` — Linux Landlock LSM.
+- `duh.adapters.sandbox.network` — network-egress policy used by
+  the `Bash`, `Docker`, and `HTTP` tools.
+- `duh.adapters.sandbox.policy` — policy struct passed into
+  `ToolContext.sandbox_policy`.
+
+`duh.security.path_policy.PathPolicy` restricts FS access per tool.
+`ReadTool.__init__` accepts a `path_policy=...` argument.
+
+The PEP 578 audit hook bridge in `duh.kernel.audit` is **telemetry,
+not enforcement**: it observes events like `open`,
+`socket.connect`, `subprocess.Popen`, `ctypes.dlopen`, sensitive
+imports (`pickle`, `marshal`), and fans them out to the hook
+registry as `HookEvent.AUDIT` so SIEM rules can act. Enforcement
+still comes from sandboxing.
+
+### 4.4 The lethal trifecta
+
+`duh.security.trifecta` encodes Simon Willison's exfiltration
+capability matrix:
+
+```python
+LETHAL_TRIFECTA = (
+    Capability.READ_PRIVATE | Capability.READ_UNTRUSTED
+    | Capability.NETWORK_EGRESS
+)
+```
+
+`compute_session_capabilities(tools)` unions every tool's declared
+`capabilities`. `check_trifecta(caps, acknowledged=False)` raises
+`LethalTrifectaError` when all three bits are lit without explicit
+ack. Ack is surfaced through `EngineConfig.trifecta_acknowledged`
+and comes from the `--acknowledge-trifecta` CLI flag.
+
+### 4.5 Other guardrails
+
+- `duh.kernel.redact.redact_secrets` scrubs API keys, PEM blocks,
+  GitHub/AWS tokens, and URL-embedded passwords from tool output
+  before it reaches the model.
+- `duh.adapters.approvers.TieredApprover` blocks destructive git
+  commands (`git push --force`, `git reset --hard`, `git clean -f`,
+  `git branch -D`) across *all* approval tiers, including
+  `FULL_AUTO`. Git safety is a floor, not a dial.
+- `duh.kernel.file_size_guard.check_file_size` refuses reads
+  estimated at > 50 % of the model's context window.
+- `duh.kernel.untrusted` also raises `TaintLossError` when strict
+  mode is enabled and a str op silently drops a tag.
+
+---
+
+## 5. Threading and concurrency
+
+D.U.H. is single-process and single-event-loop. It does not create
+OS threads (other than those implicit in `httpx` / `asyncio`).
+Concurrency is achieved via asyncio primitives.
+
+### 5.1 Concurrency inside the loop
+
+Within one turn, `duh.kernel.loop.query` groups consecutive
+read-only tool-use blocks and dispatches them concurrently:
+
+```python
+tasks = [asyncio.create_task(_execute_block(b, deps)) for b in group]
+outcomes = await asyncio.gather(*tasks)
+```
+
+Mutating tool blocks always run sequentially through
+`_execute_block_stream`. Ordering matters: a `Read` of a file that
+the previous `Write` touched must see the post-write state.
+
+### 5.2 `QueryGuard`
+
+`duh.kernel.query_guard.QueryGuard` is an `asyncio.Lock`-backed
+state machine with three states: `IDLE → DISPATCHING → RUNNING → IDLE`.
+It prevents concurrent `engine.run()` invocations from racing. In
+`cancel_on_new` mode (used by the TUI), a new prompt cancels the
+in-flight query's `asyncio.Task` instead of raising.
+
+Generation numbers make transitions idempotent: stale callbacks can
+check `generation` and exit without flipping state.
+
+### 5.3 Background jobs
+
+`duh.kernel.job_queue.JobQueue` holds an `asyncio.Semaphore` capped
+at `MAX_CONCURRENT_JOBS = 5`. Submitted coroutines become
+`asyncio.Task`s that transition `pending → running → completed
+| failed`. Finished jobs age out FIFO past `MAX_COMPLETED_RETAINED
+= 50`. This is used by `/jobs` and by the `Task` tool.
+
+### 5.4 Shutdown
+
+`duh.kernel.signals.ShutdownHandler` registers SIGTERM/SIGINT/SIGQUIT
+on the running loop. Cleanup callbacks run LIFO under a shared
+5-second deadline. A second SIGINT/SIGTERM forces immediate
+`sys.exit(1)`. SIGQUIT dumps every thread's stack via
+`faulthandler.dump_traceback`.
+
+### 5.5 File tracker diffs
+
+`FileTracker.diff_summary` does a single batched
+`asyncio.create_subprocess_exec` of `git diff --stat --
+file1 file2 …` with a 5-second wait-for. It never blocks the
+event loop. A synchronous `diff_summary_sync` is kept for legacy
+REPL paths but is marked deprecated.
+
+---
+
+## 6. Observability
+
+`duh.adapters.structured_logging.StructuredLogger` (passed to
+`Engine(structured_logger=...)`) emits JSON-lines records for
+`session_start`, `model_request`, `model_response`, `tool_call`,
+`tool_result`, and `error`. `duh.kernel.audit` forwards PEP 578
+events to the hook bus.
+
+`Engine.cost_summary()` formats per-turn and total input/output
+tokens plus estimated cost, using the pricing table in
+`duh.kernel.tokens._MODEL_PRICING` (pattern-matched on substrings for
+unknown models). `CacheTracker.summary()` shows read-ratio and cache
+break status.
+
+In-session error buffer: `Engine._record_session_error` keeps the
+last 100 error events (both `error` and
+`tool_result` with `is_error=True`). `/errors` reads this buffer.
+
+---
+
+## 7. Tradeoffs and non-goals
+
+### 7.1 Deliberate tradeoffs
+
+- **Provider-agnostic loop over SDK-native loops.** Every adapter
+  pays translation cost. We chose uniformity over performance
+  because the same UI / session / tools must work for ≥6 providers.
+- **Heuristic token counting.** `CHARS_PER_TOKEN = 4` is
+  conservative; real tokenizers produce fewer tokens on English
+  prose. We trade a few hundred tokens of budget for zero
+  tokenizer-dependency in the kernel.
+- **Taint tracking only on `str`.** Bytes, ints, and booleans don't
+  carry tags. Multi-part f-strings silently drop taint because
+  CPython's `BUILD_STRING` bytecode concatenates below the Python
+  level. The `__format__` override covers single-variable f-strings.
+- **In-memory message history, disk-based session auto-save.** A
+  session is fully in-memory during execution; `SessionStore.save`
+  happens after each turn. A crash mid-turn loses the last assistant
+  turn. This is acceptable for a coding agent; the alternative is a
+  transactional message log the kernel has no appetite for.
+- **Approval gate returns `{"allowed": …}` dicts, not booleans.** So
+  adapters can add structured reasons, integrate with audit logs,
+  and carry hints (e.g. "always allow") back to the UI.
+- **Read-only parallel, mutating sequential.** Read-only tools are
+  safe to gather; mutating tools can't interleave their on-disk
+  effects. This is a hard rule, not a heuristic.
+
+### 7.2 Non-goals
+
+- **Not a multi-agent coordination framework.** Sub-agents
+  (`duh.tools.agent_tool.AgentTool`, `duh.tools.swarm_tool.SwarmTool`)
+  spawn child engines with `DEPs` pre-filled and a small prompt, but
+  D.U.H. has no scheduler, no message bus, no consensus protocol.
+- **Not a persistence engine.** Memory is a flat file with Markdown
+  frontmatter. Sessions are JSON on disk. There is no database.
+- **Not a sandbox.** `duh/adapters/sandbox/` wraps the OS primitives;
+  the kernel doesn't enforce. If Seatbelt / Landlock aren't
+  installed, the sandbox shell is a no-op.
+- **Not a provider SDK.** The adapters are thin wrappers. We don't
+  expose advanced provider features (batch API, fine-tuning, logs)
+  to the kernel, because they don't fit the agentic loop.
+- **Not a web service.** `duh.bridge` exposes an NDJSON protocol
+  for the official Claude Code / OpenAI stream-json SDKs, but D.U.H.
+  itself is a CLI.
+
+### 7.3 What the project is
+
+A small kernel (≈7 .py files in `duh/kernel/` are the load-bearing
+ones; the rest are either pure data or single-purpose utilities),
+wrapped by ports, adapted by adapters, driven by a CLI. The pieces
+compose. The tests in `tests/unit/` test each piece in isolation;
+integration tests in `tests/integration/` exercise the whole stack
+against the stub provider. If you want to change behaviour without
+changing the kernel, you swap an adapter. If you want to change
+behaviour inside the kernel, the rule is the one at the top of
+`duh/kernel/loop.py`: pass all tests, reveal intent, no duplication,
+no unnecessary complexity.
+
+---
+
+## 8. Where to look next
+
+- **Build something end-to-end:** the [TUTORIAL](TUTORIAL.md) walks
+  through installing D.U.H., running a stub-mode session, and
+  implementing + registering a custom tool.
+- **Look up a specific symbol:** [API](API.md) lists every public
+  class and function in `duh.kernel` and `duh.ports` with signatures
+  copied verbatim from the source.
+- **Read the source:** the kernel is under 8 000 lines total. Start
+  at `duh/kernel/loop.py:query`, then `duh/kernel/engine.py:Engine.run`,
+  then `duh/kernel/deps.py:Deps`. Everything else hangs off those
+  three.
